etymologies: late 19th century; earliest use found in George Meredith (1828–1909), novelist and poet. From Middle French agelaste person who never laughs from ancient Greek ἀγέλαστος not laughing from ἀ- + γελασ-, stem (also seen in γελαστός laughable, γελαστής laugher) of γελᾶν to laugh + -τος, suffix forming verbal adjectives

definitions: A person who never laughs; one who has no sense of humour.

notes.text: Chiefly with reference to Rabelais's use of the French word: see the etymology.
